From 41eaeb5c497097d644993d4426e1623bff79534d Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Bill Denney <wdenney@humanpredictions.com>
Date: Wed, 20 May 2026 21:55:44 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] Expose AppendOption / RemoveOptions writers for widget /Opt
 arrays
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Add two new public APIs:

  FPDFAnnot_AppendOption(FPDF_FORMHANDLE hHandle,
                         FPDF_ANNOTATION annot,
                         FPDF_WIDESTRING label);

  FPDFAnnot_RemoveOptions(FPDF_FORMHANDLE hHandle,
                          FPDF_ANNOTATION annot);

The reader side already exposes the /Opt array via
FPDFAnnot_GetOptionCount() + FPDFAnnot_GetOptionLabel() +
FPDFAnnot_IsOptionSelected(), but there is no symmetric writer.
Embedders that compose programmatically-generated PDFs (e.g.
populating a listbox/combobox at fill time from a database) currently
have to either bake the options in at PDF-creation time or fall back
to a private dictionary mutation through the structural editing API.

The append-one-and-clear-all shape mirrors the existing pair
FPDFAnnot_AddInkStroke() + FPDFAnnot_RemoveInkList(), which is the
established precedent in this header for array-valued mutators.
Replacing the whole array is "RemoveOptions then loop AppendOption";
extending the array is "loop AppendOption"; clearing is just
"RemoveOptions". This avoids the double-pointer-of-FPDF_WIDESTRING
ABI a single-shot SetOptions would need.

Implementation notes:

* /Opt is a field-dict attribute that can be inherited from an
  ancestor form field. AppendOption() detects inheritance and, on
  first append, copies the inherited array down onto the terminal
  field's own dictionary before appending the new entry. Without
  this, writes to a non-root child of an /Opt-bearing parent would
  silently mutate the parent (and thus every other sibling that
  inherits from it).
* RemoveOptions() only removes /Opt from the terminal field's own
  dict; an inherited /Opt remains visible via GetOption* afterwards.
  The doc comment makes this explicit.
* Both new APIs route through new core methods
  CPDF_FormField::AppendOption() and CPDF_FormField::RemoveOptions(),
  CHECK()ed for HasOptField() like the existing readers.
* /Opt entries are written as single-label CPDF_String objects.
  PDF allows entries to be two-element [export_value, label]
  CPDF_Array entries instead — that variant is intentionally
  deferred; it can ship as a future overload taking an optional
  export-value argument without breaking this API.

Tested via six new FPDFAnnotEmbedderTest cases against
combobox_form.pdf and multiple_form_types.pdf:
  * AppendOptionCombobox          - appends + round-trips a label,
                                    then appends a second label
  * AppendOptionInvalidArgs       - NULL form / annot / label
  * AppendOptionWrongAnnotationType - textfield returns -1
  * RemoveOptionsCombobox         - removes /Opt, verifies
                                    GetOptionCount returns -1,
                                    then re-appends to a fresh /Opt
  * RemoveOptionsInvalidArgs      - NULL form / annot
  * RemoveOptionsWrongAnnotationType - textfield returns false

Change-Id: I502beb8b78a18256eb147919fe7b73dbf012b106
